TEXT: The applicants , Mr PERSON and PERSON , are NORP nationals who were born in DATE and DATE respectively and live in ORG . The respondent Government are represented by PERSON GPE , Representative of GPE at ORG .
The facts of the case , as submitted by the parties , may be summarised as follows .
In DATE the first applicant received a position at ORG and moved to ORG together with his wife ( “ the second applicant ” ) .
In DATE the applicants sued ORG and ORG for the alleged failure to grant them a flat in accordance with NORP law .

On DATE ORG partly granted the applicants’ claims and placed them on a waiting list , ordering that ORG provide the family with housing in accordance with the existing order of precedence . ORG dismissed the claims against ORG .
On DATE ORG upheld the judgment on appeal and held ORG jointly liable for allocation of a flat to the applicants .
On DATE the bailiffs began enforcement but the judgments could not be enforced as the order of precedence had not been determined by ORG .
At the ORG initiative , on DATE the ORG of ORG varied the previous judgments by way of supervisory review and held that the applicants were to receive a flat without further delay .
On DATE the applicants accepted the flat which had been offered to them by ORG .
